Nothing is untenable. Though selfless surrender makes sadhana more efficient, sadhana without selfless surrender is also fine!
 
Even if one's mind is filled with reasonable material desires (marriage, children, job, health etc), one can still do sadhana. Sadhana then takes care of one's material and spiritual needs and increases surrender and selflessness in one *over the time*.
 
Bottomline: Good sadhana increases selfless surrender and selfless surrender promotes better sadhana. This is a positive feedback loop. One should somehow or the other break through. Break the impasse and just start some sadhana. Don't fear that something bad will happen or that you will not be able to do it. Just pick a sadhana and take the plunge!
 
*        *        *
 
